#ffdf9f;\"| '''201'''\n|-\n! [[2019 Moto2 season|2019]]\n! Moto2\n! [[KTM]]\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|QAT]]<br />{{small|12}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 Argentine motorcycle Grand Prix|ARG]]<br />{{small|6}}\n|style=\"background:#efcfff;\"| [[2019 Motorcycle Grand Prix of the Americas|AME]]<br />{{small|Ret}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 Spanish motorcycle Grand Prix|SPA]]<br />{{small|5}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 French motorcycle Grand Prix|FRA]]<br />{{small|4}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 Italian motorcycle Grand Prix|ITA]]<br />{{small|15}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix|CAT]]<br />{{small|11}}\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| [[2019 Dutch TT|NED]]<br />{{small|2}}\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| [[2019 German motorcycle Grand Prix|GER]]<br />{{small|2}}\n|style=\"background:#efcfff;\"| [[2019 Czech Republic motorcycle Grand Prix|CZE]]<br />{{small|Ret}}\n|style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| [[2019 Austrian motorcycle Grand Prix|AUT]]<br />{{small|1}}\n|style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\"| [[2019 British motorcycle Grand Prix|GBR]]<br />{{small|3}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 San Marino and Rimini's Coast motorcycle Grand Prix|RSM]]<br />{{small|6}}\n|style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| [[2019 Aragon motorcycle Grand Prix|ARA]]<br />{{small|1}}\n|style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| [[2019 Thailand motorcycle Grand Prix|THA]]<br />{{small|2}}\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| [[2019 Japanese motorcycle Grand Prix|JPN]]<br />{{small|12}}\n|style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| [[2019 Australian motorcycle Grand Prix|AUS]]<br />{{small|1}}\n|style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| [[2019 Malaysian motorcycle Grand Prix|MAL]]<br />{{small|1}}\n|style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| [[2019 Valencian Community motorcycle Grand Prix|VAL]]<br />{{small|1}}\n!style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 2nd\n!style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| 259\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.motogp.com/en/riders/Brad+Binder Brad Binder's profile on MotoGP.com]\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Ajo Motorsport}}\n{{125 cc Motorcycle World Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binder, Brad}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:125cc World Championship riders]]\n[[Category:Moto3 World Championship riders]]\n[[Category:Moto2 World Championship riders]]\n[[Category:People from Potchefstroom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African motorcycle racer}}\n{{Infobox motorcycle rider\n| name              = Brad Binder\n| image             = Brad Binder Silverstone 2013.jpg\n| caption           = Binder at the [[2013 British motorcycle Grand Prix|2013 British Grand Prix]]\n| nationality       = South African\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1995|08|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Potchefstroom]], South Africa\n| Current team      = [[Red Bull KTM Factory Racing]]\n| Bike number       = 33\n| Moto2 Active years   = [[2017 Moto2 season|2017]]\u2013[[2019 Moto2 season|2019]]\n| Moto2 Manufacturers  = [[KTM]]\n| Moto2 Championships  = 0\n| Moto2 Last season    = 2019\n| Moto2 Last position  = 2nd (259 pts)\n| Moto2 Race Starts    = 52\n| Moto2 Race Wins      = 8\n| Moto2 Podiums        = 15\n| Moto2 Poles          = 1\n| Moto2 Fastest laps   = 3\n| Moto2 Total Points   = 585\n| Moto3 Active years  = {{MGP|2012}}\u2013[[2016 Moto3 season|2016]]\n| Moto3 Manufacturers = [[Kalex]] [[KTM]], [[Eskil Suter|Suter]] [[Honda]], [[Mahindra & Mahindra|Mahindra]], [[KTM]]\n| Moto3 Championships = 1 ([[2016 Moto3 season|2016]])\n| Moto3 Race Starts   = 88\n| Moto3 Race Wins     = 7\n| Moto3 Podiums       = 20\n| Moto3 Poles         = 6\n| Moto3 Fastest laps  = 7\n| Moto3 Total Points  = 677\n| Moto3 Last season   = 2016\n| Moto3 Last position = 1st (319 pts)\n| 125 Active years  = {{MGP|2011}}\n| 125 Manufacturers = [[Aprilia]]\n| 125 Championships = 0\n| 125 Race Starts   = 5\n| 125 Race Wins     = 0\n| 125 Podiums       = 0\n| 125 Poles         = 0\n| 125 Fastest laps  = 0\n| 125 Total Points  = 0\n| 125 Last season   = 2011\n| 125 Last position = NC (0 pts)\n| website           = {{URL|https://bradbinder41.com/|Brad Binder 41}}\n}}\n'''Brad Binder''' (born 11 August 1995) is a [[Grand Prix motorcycle racing|Grand Prix motorcycle racer]] from [[South Africa]]. In November 2019 he was confirmed as a factory KTM rider in [[MotoGP]] class for [[2020 MotoGP season|the 2020 season]],<ref name=\"crash 24 Oct\">[https://www.crash.net/motogp/news/931888/1/ktm-shakeup-binder-factory-motogp-team-lecuona-tech3 KTM 2020 shake-up: Binder to factory MotoGP team, Lecuona Tech3] crash.net, 24 October 2019, Retrieved 21 November 2019</ref> replacing [[Johann Zarco]] who had abandoned his factory ride earlier in the year.\n\nPreviously he had competed in the Moto2 class during 2019 with KTM satellite team [[Tech3]],<ref name=\"crash 24 Oct\"/> finishing the championship in second place. He was also known for winning the [[2016 Moto3 season|2016 Moto3 World Championship]]. Prior to moving up to Grand Prix level, Binder contested three seasons of the [[Red Bull MotoGP Rookies Cup]], with a best finish of fifth overall in the championship standings.\n\nAt the [[2016 Spanish motorcycle Grand Prix]] in Jerez, Binder became the first South African to win a motorcycle Grand Prix since [[Jon Ekerold]] won the 350&nbsp;cc class at the [[Italian motorcycle Grand Prix#Winners of the Nations motorcycle Grand Prix|1981 Italian motorcycle Grand Prix]]. From [[2017 Moto2 season|2017]], Binder raced in the Moto2 class having agreed a deal with [[Ajo Motorsport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2016/09/13/red-bull-ktm-ajo-take-on-moto2-in-2017/210892|title=Red Bull KTM Ajo take on Moto2 in 2017|publisher=Dorna Sports|date=13 September 2016|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBinder's younger brother [[Darryn Binder|Darryn]] is also a motorcycle racer, and competed alongside Brad in Moto3 in 2015 and 2016.\n\n==Career==\n===125cc World Championship===\n====2011====\nBinder started his Grand Prix career in the 125cc class riding an [[Aprilia]] in the [[2011 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2011]] season with his bike number as 14. Binder finished the season pointless, with his best position being a 17th place in Indianapolis.\n\n===Moto3 World Championship===\n====2012====\nIn 2012 started racing in the [[Kalex]] [[KTM]] with his bike number changed to 41. Binder's first Moto3 point came at the [[2012 Portuguese motorcycle Grand Prix]]. 2012 was a crash-filled season for Binder, with seven crashes. Binder scored four times in the season, with his best result of fourth place coming in Valencia. He finished the season at 21st place with 24 points.\n\n====2013====\nIn 2013 Binder switched from KTM to [[Eskil Suter|Suter]] [[Honda]] and in the same year changed to [[Mahindra & Mahindra|Mahindra]] bike. 2013 was a consistent year for Binder; he scored in 14 out of the 18 races, his best result being a fourth place at Spain; he finished the final standings at 13th place with 66 points.\n\n===Moto2 World Championship===\n====2019====\nIn 2019 he joined KTM's [[Tech3|Tech3 Moto2]] satellite team finishing the championship in second place,<!-- Brad Binder moved straight to the factory team while fellow rookie Iker Lecuona replaces the South African at Tech3 --><ref name=\"crash 24 Oct\"/> and will move up to MotoGP with Red Bull KTM Factory Racing for the 2020 season.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Grand Prix motorcycle racing===\n====By season====\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align:right\n!Season\n!Class\n!Motorcycle\n!Team\n!Race\n!Win\n!Podium\n![[Pole Position|Pole]]\n!FLap\n!Pts\n!Plcd\n|-\n! {{MGP|2011}}\n| 125cc\n| [[Aprilia]]\n| Andaluc\u00eda Banca C\u00edvica\n| 5\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| NC\n|-\n! {{MGP|2012}}\n| Moto3\n| [[Kalex]] [[KTM]]\n| RW Racing GP\n| 17\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 24\n| 2