{"title_page": "Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation", "text_new": "The Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation is a [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit organization]]\u00a0founded by Adam Lowe in 2009 and located in Madrid, Spain. It develops new techniques in digital recording and processing to document artworks and cultural heritage of many different types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-factory-of-fakes|title=The Factory of Fakes: How a workshop uses digital technology to craft perfect copies of imperilled art|last=Zalewski|first=Daniel|date=21/11/2016|website=The New Yorker|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4f14250-ca3f-11e9-af46-b09e8bfe60c0|title=How digital scanning can help save art works and buildings|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|date=30/8/2019|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2020/02/29/5e57cfacfdddfff83a8b471f.html|title=Los copiadores legales del arte antiguo|last=G\u00f3mez|first=Virginia|date=29/02/2020|website=El Mundo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoy.es/sociedad/taller-prodigios-20191109002812-ntvo.html|title=El taller de los prodigios|last=Guerrero|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=10/11/2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/apollo-awards-digital-innovation-year/|title=Digital Innovation of the Year: The Apollo Awards 2014|last=|first=|date=03/12/2014|website=Apollo Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> It is known for its facsimiles (high-resolution physical copies) of sites and objects such as the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|title=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|last=Glass|first=Nick|date=15/11/2017|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12/04/2020}}</ref> two monumental [[lamassu]] sculptures from [[Nimrud]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/mosul-statues-unveiling-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mosul takes delivery of recreated icons|last=Guy|first=Jack|date=28/10/2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-smashed-by-jihadists-rises-up-after-global-effort-g0dbphfd5|title=Art smashed by jihadists rises up after global effort|last=Keeley|first=Guy|date=22/10/2019|website=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordantimes.com/news/region/replicas-assyrian-statues-smashed-daesh-unveiled-iraqs-mosul|title=Replicas of Assyrian statues smashed by Daesh unveiled in Iraq\u2019s Mosul|last=AFP|first=|date=24/10/2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> and the [[Sebastiano del Piombo|Borgherini Chapel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/372727/how-michelangelo-and-sebastianos-roman-chapel-was-recreated-in-london/|title=How Michelangelo and Sebastiano\u2019s Roman Chapel Was Recreated in London|last=McEwan|first=Olivia|date=17/04/2017|website=Hyperallergic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> The\u00a0 Foundation also mounts exhibitions and trains local communities across the world in the use of digital recording technologies, and is active in contemporary debates about the functions and value of facsimiles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/49/exhibitions|title=Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/171/trainings-collaborations|title=Trainings and Collaborations|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-apollo-podcast-adam-lowe/|title=The Apollo podcast: Adam Lowe|last=|first=|date=04/05/2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> It states that its aim is to \u201cbreak down the barriers between traditional and digital arts and demonstrate the importance of documenting, monitoring, studying, recreating and disseminating the world\u2019s cultural heritage.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/aboutus|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFactum Foundation works closely with [[Factum Arte]], and was established in order to take over Factum Arte\u2019s non-profit work relating to cultural heritage.\u00a0 \n\n== Cultural heritage projects ==\nNotable facsimiles made by Factum Foundation include: \n\n* The [[KV62|tomb of Tutankhamun]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-24478909|title=Which would you rather visit - a fake tomb or a real one?|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=08/11/2013|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\n* Rooms from the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]] in the [[Valley of the Kings]]. Scanning of all extant fragments from the tomb is underway, and Factum states that the finished facsimile of the tomb will be \u2018by some measures... even more complete than the original as it now stands\u2019, as it will incorporate fragments removed from the tomb in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1502/the-tomb-of-seti-recording-and-facsimile|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> \u00a0\n* Two monumental lamassu and all extant wall and floor reliefs from the throne room of the North-West Palace of [[Ashurnasirpal II]] at Nimrud \n\n* The [[:it:Polittico_Griffoni|Polittico Griffoni]], a 15th-century Bolognese altarpiece which was dismantled in the 18th century, and whose 16 separate painted panels are now in museums across the world \n* [[Raphael]]\u2019s ''Sacrifice at Lystra'', one of the [[Raphael Cartoons]] now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vam.ac.uk/blog/projects/exciting-new-plans-for-the-raphael-cartoons-and-raphael-court|title=Exciting new plans for the Raphael Cartoons and Raphael Court|last=Steel|first=Sophie|date=01/10/2019|website=V&A blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1578/the-tomb-of-raphael-in-the-pantheon Tomb of Raphael] from the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] \n* Several artworks from [[Horace Walpole]]\u2019s collections for [[Strawberry Hill House]]\n* Two sketchbooks by [[Antonio Canova]]\n\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1331/MINIATURE-BOOK-SCANNER Offiziolo di Carlo VIII] \n* The Borgherini Chapel \n\n\nOther projects have sought to \u2018digitally restore\u2019 artworks to a former state, to recreate lost artworks, or to show artworks in a changed form. Projects include: \u00a0\n\n* Digital restoration of a [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1351/canovas-equestrian-statue monumental plaster horse] by Canova, whose original is now in fragments \n\n* Digital restoration and restored facsimile of the vandalised sacred cave of [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1289/the-sacred-cave-of-kamukuwak%C3%83 Kamukuwak\u00e1] \u00a0\n* Recreation of Raphael\u2019s painting [[Christ Falling on the Way to Calvary|Lo Spasimo]] as a painting on board. The painting had been [[Transfer of panel paintings|transferred from wooden boards to canvas]] by restorers in the early 19th century, so the recreation attempts to recover an earlier stage in the history of the work. \u00a0\n* The re-creation of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]]'s lost silver world map \n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== Technologies for recording\u00a0 ===\nThe Factum Foundation develops many of its own recording and processing technologies, which include the Lucida 3D Scanner (designed by [[Manuel Franquelo]] with the support of Factum Foundation and Factum Arte),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6-8 February 2019|title=A REVIEW OF RECORDING TECHNOLOGIES FOR DIGITAL FABRICATIONIN HERITAGE CONSERVATION|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/2fbe/810138da092f9ba3fcd09b430690c5e310f0.pdf|journal=The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences, Volume XLII-2/W9, 2019 8th Intl. Workshop 3D-ARCH \u201c3D Virtual Reconstruction and Visualization of Complex Architectures\u201d|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Del Sette, Patan\u00e9 et al.|first=|date=02/06/2017|title=Automated displacement measurements on historical canvases|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40494-017-0135-4|journal=Heritage Science|volume=5|pages=|via=Springer}}</ref> the Veronica Scanner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/23/gallery-offers-visitors-a-3d-digital-sculpture-in-four-seconds|title=Gallery offers visitors a 3D digital sculpture in four seconds|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|date=23/07/2016|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> and several book and manuscript scanners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/36/recording|title=Technology: Recording|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> The Foundation also uses established and in-development recording techniques such as [[photogrammetry]], [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag_fa/1343/panoramic-composite-photography panoramic composite photography], [[Lidar|LiDAR]] and [[White light scanner|structured light scanning]]. \n\n=== Technologies for making facsimiles\u00a0 ===\nTo make its facsimiles Factum Foundation employs a range of traditional and new technologies, often in combination. Technologies include [[Numerical control|CNC-milling]], several types of [[3D printing]], [[Molding (process)|molding]] and [[Plaster cast|plaster casting]], [[Lost-wax casting|bronze casting]], inkjet printing using an in-house printer, sculptural finishing, [[gilding]], [[scagliola]], [[Printmaking|print-making]], and the use of traditional [[Conservation and restoration of cultural heritage|restoration/conservation]] techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/40/outputs|title=Technology: Outputs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.factumfoundation.org/ Official website]\n", "text_old": "The Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation is a [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit organization]]\u00a0founded by Adam Lowe in 2009 and located in Madrid, Spain. It develops new techniques in digital recording and processing to document artworks and cultural heritage of many different types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-factory-of-fakes|title=The Factory of Fakes: How a workshop uses digital technology to craft perfect copies of imperilled art|last=Zalewski|first=Daniel|date=21/11/2016|website=The New Yorker|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13/4/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4f14250-ca3f-11e9-af46-b09e8bfe60c0|title=How digital scanning can help save art works and buildings|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|date=30/8/2019|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2020/02/29/5e57cfacfdddfff83a8b471f.html|title=Los copiadores legales del arte antiguo|last=G\u00f3mez|first=Virginia|date=29/02/2020|website=El Mundo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoy.es/sociedad/taller-prodigios-20191109002812-ntvo.html|title=El taller de los prodigios|last=Guerrero|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=10/11/2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/apollo-awards-digital-innovation-year/|title=Digital Innovation of the Year: The Apollo Awards 2014|last=|first=|date=03/12/2014|website=Apollo Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> It is known for its facsimiles (high-resolution physical copies) of sites and objects such as the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|title=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|last=Glass|first=Nick|date=15/11/2017|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12/04/2020}}</ref> two monumental [[lamassu]] sculptures from [[Nimrud]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/mosul-statues-unveiling-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mosul takes delivery of recreated icons|last=Guy|first=Jack|date=28/10/2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-smashed-by-jihadists-rises-up-after-global-effort-g0dbphfd5|title=Art smashed by jihadists rises up after global effort|last=Keeley|first=Guy|date=22/10/2019|website=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordantimes.com/news/region/replicas-assyrian-statues-smashed-daesh-unveiled-iraqs-mosul|title=Replicas of Assyrian statues smashed by Daesh unveiled in Iraq\u2019s Mosul|last=AFP|first=|date=24/10/2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> and the [[Sebastiano del Piombo|Borgherini Chapel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/372727/how-michelangelo-and-sebastianos-roman-chapel-was-recreated-in-london/|title=How Michelangelo and Sebastiano\u2019s Roman Chapel Was Recreated in London|last=McEwan|first=Olivia|date=17/04/2017|website=Hyperallergic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> The\u00a0 Foundation also mounts exhibitions and trains local communities across the world in the use of digital recording technologies, and is active in contemporary debates about the functions and value of facsimiles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/49/exhibitions|title=Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/171/trainings-collaborations|title=Trainings and Collaborations|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-apollo-podcast-adam-lowe/|title=The Apollo podcast: Adam Lowe|last=|first=|date=04/05/2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> It states that its aim is to \u201cbreak down the barriers between traditional and digital arts and demonstrate the importance of documenting, monitoring, studying, recreating and disseminating the world\u2019s cultural heritage.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/aboutus|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFactum Foundation works closely with [[Factum Arte]], and was established in order to take over Factum Arte\u2019s non-profit work relating to cultural heritage.\u00a0 \n\n== Cultural heritage projects ==\nNotable facsimiles made by Factum Foundation include: \n\n* The [[KV62|tomb of Tutankhamun]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-24478909|title=Which would you rather visit - a fake tomb or a real one?|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=08/11/2013|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\n* Rooms from the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]] in the [[Valley of the Kings]]. Scanning of all extant fragments from the tomb is underway, and Factum states that the finished facsimile of the tomb will be \u2018by some measures... even more complete than the original as it now stands\u2019, as it will incorporate fragments removed from the tomb in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1502/the-tomb-of-seti-recording-and-facsimile|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> \u00a0\n* Two monumental lamassu and all extant wall and floor reliefs from the throne room of the North-West Palace of [[Ashurnasirpal II]] at Nimrud \n\n* The [[:it:Polittico_Griffoni|Polittico Griffoni]], a 15th-century Bolognese altarpiece which was dismantled in the 18th century, and whose 16 separate painted panels are now in museums across the world \n* [[Raphael]]\u2019s ''Sacrifice at Lystra'', one of the [[Raphael Cartoons]] now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vam.ac.uk/blog/projects/exciting-new-plans-for-the-raphael-cartoons-and-raphael-court|title=Exciting new plans for the Raphael Cartoons and Raphael Court|last=Steel|first=Sophie|date=01/10/2019|website=V&A blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1578/the-tomb-of-raphael-in-the-pantheon Tomb of Raphael] from the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] \n* Several artworks from [[Horace Walpole]]\u2019s collections for [[Strawberry Hill House]]\n* Two sketchbooks by [[Antonio Canova]]\n\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1331/MINIATURE-BOOK-SCANNER Offiziolo di Carlo VIII] \n* The Borgherini Chapel \n\n\nOther projects have sought to \u2018digitally restore\u2019 artworks to a former state, to recreate lost artworks, or to show artworks in a changed form. Projects include: \u00a0\n\n* Digital restoration of a [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1351/canovas-equestrian-statue monumental plaster horse] by Canova, whose original is now in fragments \n\n* Digital restoration and restored facsimile of the vandalised sacred cave of [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1289/the-sacred-cave-of-kamukuwak%C3%83 Kamukuwak\u00e1] \u00a0\n* Recreation of Raphael\u2019s painting [[Christ Falling on the Way to Calvary|Lo Spasimo]] as a painting on board. The painting had been [[Transfer of panel paintings|transferred from wooden boards to canvas]] by restorers in the early 19th century, so the recreation attempts to recover an earlier stage in the history of the work. \u00a0\n* The re-creation of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]]'s lost silver world map \n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== Technologies for recording\u00a0 ===\nThe Factum Foundation develops many of its own recording and processing technologies, which include the Lucida 3D Scanner (designed by [[Manuel Franquelo]] with the support of Factum Foundation and Factum Arte),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6-8 February 2019|title=A REVIEW OF RECORDING TECHNOLOGIES FOR DIGITAL FABRICATIONIN HERITAGE CONSERVATION|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/2fbe/810138da092f9ba3fcd09b430690c5e310f0.pdf|journal=The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences, Volume XLII-2/W9, 2019 8th Intl. Workshop 3D-ARCH \u201c3D Virtual Reconstruction and Visualization of Complex Architectures\u201d|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Del Sette, Patan\u00e9 et al.|first=|date=02/06/2017|title=Automated displacement measurements on historical canvases|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40494-017-0135-4|journal=Heritage Science|volume=5|pages=|via=Springer}}</ref> the Veronica Scanner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/23/gallery-offers-visitors-a-3d-digital-sculpture-in-four-seconds|title=Gallery offers visitors a 3D digital sculpture in four seconds|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|date=23/07/2016|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> and several book and manuscript scanners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/36/recording|title=Technology: Recording|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref> The Foundation also uses established and in-development recording techniques such as [[photogrammetry]], [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag_fa/1343/panoramic-composite-photography panoramic composite photography], [[Lidar|LiDAR]] and [[White light scanner|structured light scanning]]. \n\n=== Technologies for making facsimiles\u00a0 ===\nTo make its facsimiles Factum Foundation employs a range of traditional and new technologies, often in combination. Technologies include [[Numerical control|CNC-milling]], several types of [[3D printing]], [[Molding (process)|molding]] and [[Plaster cast|plaster casting]], [[Lost-wax casting|bronze casting]], inkjet printing using an in-house printer, sculptural finishing, [[gilding]], [[scagliola]], [[Printmaking|print-making]], and the use of traditional [[Conservation and restoration of cultural heritage|restoration/conservation]] techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/40/outputs|title=Technology: Outputs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11/04/2020}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.factumfoundation.org/ Official website]\n", "name_user": "Anachorism", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factum_Foundation_for_Digital_Technology_in_Conservation"}
{"title_page": "Die Glocke (hoax)", "text_new": "{{about||Schiller\u2019s poem \"Das Lied von der Glocke\"|Song of the Bell|die Steinerne Glocke|Dresden Frauenkirche|other uses|The Bell (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Dieglock1.jpg|thumb|Artist impression of Die Glocke.]]\n\n'''''Die Glocke''''' ({{IPA-de|d\u026a \u02c8\u0261l\u0254k\u0259|lang}}, \"The Bell\") is a purported top secret [[Nazi]] scientific technological device, secret weapon, or ''[[Wunderwaffe]]''. First described by [[Poland|Polish]] journalist and author Igor Witkowski in ''Prawda o Wunderwaffe'' (2000), it was later popularized by military journalist and author [[Nick Cook (writer)|Nick Cook]] who associated it with [[Nazi occultism]], [[antigravity]] and [[Free energy suppression|free energy]] research.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Igor Witkowski.JPG|thumb|Polish author Igor Witkowski.]]\nIn his 2001 book ''The Hunt for Zero Point'', author Nick Cook identified claims about ''Die Glocke'' as having originated in the 2000 [[Polish language]] book ''Prawda o Wunderwaffe'' (The Truth About The Wonder Weapon) by Igor Witkowski. Cook described Witkowski's claims of a device called \"The Bell\" engineered by Nazi scientists that was \"a glowing, rotating contraption\" rumored to have \"some kind of antigravitational effect\", be a \"time machine\", or part of an \"[[Schutzstaffel|SS]] antigravity program\" for a flying saucer called the \"Repulsine\". Cook proposed that an SS official named [[Hans Kammler]] later secretly traded this technology to the U.S. military in exchange for his freedom.<ref name=\"Salon.com\">{{cite web |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/books/review/2002/08/05/zero_gravity/index.html |title=\"The Hunt for Zero Point\" by Nick Cook |last=Kleiner |first=Kurt |date=5 August 2002 |publisher=Salon.com |accessdate=5 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115142418/http://dir.salon.com/story/books/review/2002/08/05/zero_gravity/index.html |archivedate=15 January 2011}}</ref> Cook's publication introduced the topic in English without critically discussing the subject.<ref name=Kingsepp/> More recently, historian [[Eric Kurlander]] has discussed the topic in his 2017 book on Nazi esotericism ''Hitler's Monsters A Supernatural History of the Third Reich''. According to reviewer Julian Strube, Kurlander \"cites from the reservoir of post-war conspiracy theories\" and \"heavily relies on sensationalist accounts...mixing up contemporary sources with post-war sensationalist literature, half-truths, and fictitious accounts\".<ref name=Strube/>\n\nAccording to [[Salon (website)|Salon]] reviewer Kurt Kleiner, \"It's a story that strains credulity. But unless we're after cheap laughs, our hope when we pick up a book like this is that the author will, against the odds, build a careful, reasonable and convincing case. Cook isn't that author\". Kleiner criticized Cook's work as \"ferreting out minor inconsistencies and odd, ambiguous details which he tries to puff up into proof\", characterized the process of evaluating Cook's claims as \"untangling science from pseudo-science\", and concluded that \"what is instructive about the book is the insight we get into how [[conspiracy theories]] seduce otherwise reasonable people\".<ref name=\"Salon.com\" />\n\nSkeptical author [[Robert Sheaffer]] criticized Cook's book as \"a classic example of how to spin an exciting yarn based on almost  nothing. He visits places where it is rumored that secret UFO and antigravity research is going on...and writes about what he feels and imagines, although he discovers nothing more tangible than unsubstantiated rumors\". Sheaffer notes that claims about Die Glocke are circulated by [[UFOlogy|UFOlogists]] and conspiracy-oriented authors such as [[Jim Marrs]], Joseph P. Farrell, and antigravity proponent John Dering.<ref name=\"Sheaffer\">{{cite journal |last1=Sheaffer |first1=Robert |title=Nazi Saucers and Antigravity |journal=[[The Skeptical Inquirer]] |date=January 2009 |volume=33 |issue=1 |page=13\u201315 |url=https://skepticalinquirer.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/29/2009/01/p13.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAuthor [[Jason Colavito]] wrote that Witkowski's claims were \"recycled\" from 1960s rumors of Nazi occult science first published in ''[[Morning of the Magicians]]'', and describes Die Glocke as \"a device few outside of fringe culture think actually existed. In short, it looks to be a hoax, or at least a wild exaggeration\".<ref name=\"Colavito\">{{cite web|last1=Colavito|first1=Jason|title=Review of In Search of Aliens S01E02 \"Nazi Time Travelers\"|url=http://www.jasoncolavito.com/blog/review-of-in-search-of-aliens-s01e02-nazi-time-travelers|website=JasonColavito.com|publisher=Jason Colavito|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> Author [[Brian Dunning (author)|Brian Dunning]] states that ''Morning of the Magicians'' helped promote belief in Die Glocke and Nazi occultism, and its absence in the historical record make it \"increasingly unlikely that anything like it actually existed\". According to Dunning, \"all we have in the way of evidence is a third-hand anecdotal account of something that's desperately implausible, backed up by neither evidence nor even a corroborating account\".<ref name=\"Dunning2018\">{{cite book|author=Brian Dunning|title=Conspiracies Declassified: The Skeptoid Guide to the Truth Behind the Theories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGFEDwAAQBAJ|date=5 June 2018|publisher=Adams Media|isbn=978-1-5072-0700-0}}</ref>\n\nAuthor and historian [[Robert F. Dorr]] characterizes Die Glocke as among \"the most imaginative of the conspiracy theories\" that arose in post-[[World War II]] years, and typical of the fantasies of magical German weapons often popularized in pulp magazines such as ''[[The Police Gazette]]''.<ref name=\"Dorr2013\">{{cite book|author=Robert F. Dorr|title=Fighting Hitler's Jets: The Extraordinary Story of the American Airmen Who Beat the Luftwaffe and Defeated Nazi Germany|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-nBmAgAAQBAJ|date=15 November 2013|publisher=Voyageur Press|isbn=978-0-7603-4398-2}}</ref>\n\nSome theories circulating on Internet conspiracy sites claim that Die Glocke is located in a [[Nazi gold train]] that is buried in a tunnel beneath a mountain in [[Poland]].<ref name=Kaplan/> Duncan Roads, editor of [[Nexus (magazine)|''Nexus'' magazine]], has pointed out that the \"Nazis on the Moon trope\" is linked to wild speculations about Nazi anti-gravitational technology, such as Witkowski's Die Glocke.<ref>{{cite news |last=Power |first=Ed |date=July 18, 2019 |title=Why are we still obsessed with the idea of Nazis on the Moon? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/still-obsessed-idea-nazis-moon/|work=Daily Telegraph |location=London }}</ref>\n\nJournalist Patrick J. Kiger wrote that German propaganda of fictional ''Wunderwaffen'' combined with the secrecy surrounding actual advanced technology such as the [[V-2]] rocket captured at war's end by the U.S. military helped spawn \"sensational book-length exposes, web sites, and legions of enthusiasts who revel in rumors of science fiction-like weapons supposedly invented by Hitler\u2019s scientists\". According to Kiger, Die Glocke is a popular example of such legends and speculation, citing former [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace scientist]] David Myhra's contention that if antigravity devices actually existed, the Germans, desperate to stop the Allies advance, would have used them.<ref name=secret>{{cite web|url=http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/hitler-s-stealth-fighter-3942/nazi-secret-weapons-1#ixzz0uXSU8IRo|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226104846/http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/hitler-s-stealth-fighter-3942/nazi-secret-weapons-1|archive-date=26 February 2010|publisher=[[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]]|first=Patrick J.|last=Kiger|title=Nazi Secret Weapons|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\n*Die Glocke and other purported Nazi ''Wunderwaffen'' have been dramatized in the video game ''[[Call of Duty]]''.<ref name=\"Tack\">{{cite web |last1=Tack |first1=Daniel |title=Bringing The Horror Of Call of Duty: WWII Nazi Zombies To Life |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/08/09/bringing-the-horror-of-call-of-duty-nazi-zombies-to-life.aspx |website=Gameinformer.com |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> \n*Die Glocke figures in the backstory of the 2006 [[James Rollins]] action-adventure novel ''Black Order''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boucher |first=Rod |date=March 17, 2007 |title=Nazi master race revisited |work=The Mercury |location=Hobart, Australia |page=B9 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYJB\">{{cite web |last1=Fortier |first1=Ron |title=Black Order: A Sigma Force Novel |url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/black-order-sigma-force-novel |website=nyjournalofbooks.com |publisher=New York Journal of Books |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n*Die Glocke was the focus of a 2014 episode of ''[[In Search of Aliens]]''.<ref name=\"Colavito\" /><ref name=\"HC\">{{cite web |title=In Search of Aliens |url=https://www.history.com/shows/in-search-of-aliens/season-1/episode-2 |date=1 August 2014 |website=[[The History Channel]] |publisher=[[A&E Networks]] |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>  \n*Die Glocke figures in the backstory of the 2013 [[A. G. Riddle]] action-adventure novel ''The Atlantis Gene''. <ref name=\"Riddle2013\">{{cite book|author=A. G. Riddle|authorlink=A. G. Riddle|title=The Atlantis Gene|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2YSmwEACAAJ|accessdate=25 January 2020|series=Origin mystery|volume=1|year=2013|publisher=A. G. Riddle|isbn=978-1-940026-01-5}}</ref>\n*The structures at Wenceslas Mine are featured in Series 3 episode 6 of Abandoned Engineering on the UK TV channel [[Yesterday (TV channel)|Yesterday]]. ''Igor Witkowski'' appears on the program and explains his theory about ''Die Glocke''\n*Die Glocke is featured as a plot device in Season 4 of the [[12 Monkeys (TV series)]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Nazism and occultism]]\n* [[Nazi UFOs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist |refs=\n<ref name=Kingsepp>{{cite journal |doi=10.1163/15700593-01902009 |title=Scholarship as Simulacrum: The Case of Hitler's Monsters |journal=Aries |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=265\u2013281 |year=2019 |last1=Kingsepp |first1=Eva |quote=One of these \u2018methodologically sound\u2019 books is Nick Cook\u2019s (in)famous ''The Hunt for Zero Point: Inside the Classified World of Antigravity Technology'' (2002), where a new amazing secret Nazi super weapon, the \u201cNazi Bell\u201d/\u201cdie Glocke\u201d, was introduced to the English-speaking audience. There is no critical reflection whatsoever regarding the poor credibility regarding \u201cdie Glocke\u201d, which is not surprising, as the general impression of ''Hitler\u2019s Monsters'' is that it aims at providing support for spectacular ideas rather than critically examining them. }}</ref>\n<ref name=Strube>{{cite journal |issn=2053-7158 |last=Strube |first=Julian |editor-last1=Elwing |editor-first1=Jimmy |editor-last2=Roukema |editor-first2=Aren |title=Hitler's Monsters: A Supernatural History of the Third Reich |url=http://correspondencesjournal.com/ojs/ojs/index.php/home/article/viewFile/56/56 |journal=Correspondences: Online Journal for the Academic Study of Western Esotericism |quote=These problems resurface in the chapters of Part Three, for instance when Kurlander cites from the reservoir of post-war conspiracy theories: his jaw dropping  discussion of a topic like the alleged super weapon, die Glocke, only serves, again, to suggest that the large amount of such tales hints at some obscure kernel of truth. }}</ref>\n<ref name=Kaplan>{{cite news |last=Kaplan |first=Sarah |date=August 28, 2015 |title=A frenzy in Poland over the latest mysterious 'Nazi gold train' |work=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/08/28/a-frenzy-in-poland-over-the-latest-mysterious-nazi-gold-train/|quote=On the corners of the Internet inclined toward conspiracy, theories circulate that \"Die Glocke\" \u2013 a purported Nazi superweapon that has so far only been found in the pages of science fiction novels \u2013 might be hidden somewhere beneath those ancient mountains.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category|Die Glocke}}\n* {{cite book | last = Cook | first = Nick | authorlink = Nick Cook (writer) | title = The Hunt for Zero Point: Inside the Classified World of Antigravity Technology | publisher = Century| year = 2001 | isbn = 978-0-09-941498-8}}\n* {{cite book | last = Witkowski| first = Igor | authorlink = | title = The Truth about the Wunderwaffe | publisher = Books International Militaria| year = 2003 | url = |others=Bruce Wenham (trans) | isbn = 83-88259-16-4}}\n\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glocke}}\n[[Category:Anti-gravity]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Nazism and occultism]]\n[[Category:UFO-related phenomena]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n[[Category:Hoaxes in Germany]]\n[[Category:Paranormal hoaxes]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||Schiller\u2019s poem \"Das Lied von der Glocke\"|Song of the Bell|die Steinerne Glocke|Dresden Frauenkirche|other uses|The Bell (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Dieglock1.jpg|thumb|Artist impression of Die Glocke.]]\n\n'''''Die Glocke''''' ({{IPA-de|d\u026a \u02c8\u0261l\u0254k\u0259|lang}}, \"The Bell\") is a purported top secret [[Nazi]] scientific technological device, secret weapon, or ''[[Wunderwaffe]]''. First described by [[Poland|Polish]] journalist and author Igor Witkowski in ''Prawda o Wunderwaffe'' (2000), it was later popularized by military journalist and author [[Nick Cook (writer)|Nick Cook]] who associated it with [[Nazi occultism]], [[antigravity]] and [[Free energy suppression|free energy]] research. Mainstream reviewers have criticized claims about Die Glocke as being [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]], recycled rumors, and a [[hoax]]. Die Glocke and other alleged Nazi \"miracle weapons\" have been dramatized in video games, television shows, and novels.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:Igor Witkowski.JPG|thumb|Polish author Igor Witkowski.]]\nIn his 2001 book ''The Hunt for Zero Point'', author Nick Cook identified claims about ''Die Glocke'' as having originated in the 2000 [[Polish language]] book ''Prawda o Wunderwaffe'' (The Truth About The Wonder Weapon) by Igor Witkowski. Cook described Witkowski's claims of a device called \"The Bell\" engineered by Nazi scientists that was \"a glowing, rotating contraption\" rumored to have \"some kind of antigravitational effect\", be a \"time machine\", or part of an \"[[Schutzstaffel|SS]] antigravity program\" for a flying saucer called the \"Repulsine\". Cook proposed that an SS official named [[Hans Kammler]] later secretly traded this technology to the U.S. military in exchange for his freedom.<ref name=\"Salon.com\">{{cite web |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/books/review/2002/08/05/zero_gravity/index.html |title=\"The Hunt for Zero Point\" by Nick Cook |last=Kleiner |first=Kurt |date=5 August 2002 |publisher=Salon.com |accessdate=5 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115142418/http://dir.salon.com/story/books/review/2002/08/05/zero_gravity/index.html |archivedate=15 January 2011}}</ref> Cook's publication introduced the topic in English without critically discussing the subject.<ref name=Kingsepp/> More recently, historian [[Eric Kurlander]] has discussed the topic in his 2017 book on Nazi esotericism ''Hitler's Monsters A Supernatural History of the Third Reich''. According to reviewer Julian Strube, Kurlander \"cites from the reservoir of post-war conspiracy theories\" and \"heavily relies on sensationalist accounts...mixing up contemporary sources with post-war sensationalist literature, half-truths, and fictitious accounts\".<ref name=Strube/>\n\nAccording to [[Salon (website)|Salon]] reviewer Kurt Kleiner, \"It's a story that strains credulity. But unless we're after cheap laughs, our hope when we pick up a book like this is that the author will, against the odds, build a careful, reasonable and convincing case. Cook isn't that author\". Kleiner criticized Cook's work as \"ferreting out minor inconsistencies and odd, ambiguous details which he tries to puff up into proof\", characterized the process of evaluating Cook's claims as \"untangling science from pseudo-science\", and concluded that \"what is instructive about the book is the insight we get into how [[conspiracy theories]] seduce otherwise reasonable people\".<ref name=\"Salon.com\" />\n\nSkeptical author [[Robert Sheaffer]] criticized Cook's book as \"a classic example of how to spin an exciting yarn based on almost  nothing. He visits places where it is rumored that secret UFO and antigravity research is going on...and writes about what he feels and imagines, although he discovers nothing more tangible than unsubstantiated rumors\". Sheaffer notes that claims about Die Glocke are circulated by [[UFOlogy|UFOlogists]] and conspiracy-oriented authors such as [[Jim Marrs]], Joseph P. Farrell, and antigravity proponent John Dering.<ref name=\"Sheaffer\">{{cite journal |last1=Sheaffer |first1=Robert |title=Nazi Saucers and Antigravity |journal=[[The Skeptical Inquirer]] |date=January 2009 |volume=33 |issue=1 |page=13\u201315 |url=https://skepticalinquirer.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/29/2009/01/p13.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAuthor [[Jason Colavito]] wrote that Witkowski's claims were \"recycled\" from 1960s rumors of Nazi occult science first published in ''[[Morning of the Magicians]]'', and describes Die Glocke as \"a device few outside of fringe culture think actually existed. In short, it looks to be a hoax, or at least a wild exaggeration\".<ref name=\"Colavito\">{{cite web|last1=Colavito|first1=Jason|title=Review of In Search of Aliens S01E02 \"Nazi Time Travelers\"|url=http://www.jasoncolavito.com/blog/review-of-in-search-of-aliens-s01e02-nazi-time-travelers|website=JasonColavito.com|publisher=Jason Colavito|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> Author [[Brian Dunning (author)|Brian Dunning]] states that ''Morning of the Magicians'' helped promote belief in Die Glocke and Nazi occultism, and its absence in the historical record make it \"increasingly unlikely that anything like it actually existed\". According to Dunning, \"all we have in the way of evidence is a third-hand anecdotal account of something that's desperately implausible, backed up by neither evidence nor even a corroborating account\".<ref name=\"Dunning2018\">{{cite book|author=Brian Dunning|title=Conspiracies Declassified: The Skeptoid Guide to the Truth Behind the Theories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kGFEDwAAQBAJ|date=5 June 2018|publisher=Adams Media|isbn=978-1-5072-0700-0}}</ref>\n\nAuthor and historian [[Robert F. Dorr]] characterizes Die Glocke as among \"the most imaginative of the conspiracy theories\" that arose in post-[[World War II]] years, and typical of the fantasies of magical German weapons often popularized in pulp magazines such as ''[[The Police Gazette]]''.<ref name=\"Dorr2013\">{{cite book|author=Robert F. Dorr|title=Fighting Hitler's Jets: The Extraordinary Story of the American Airmen Who Beat the Luftwaffe and Defeated Nazi Germany|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-nBmAgAAQBAJ|date=15 November 2013|publisher=Voyageur Press|isbn=978-0-7603-4398-2}}</ref>\n\nSome theories circulating on Internet conspiracy sites claim that Die Glocke is located in a [[Nazi gold train]] that is buried in a tunnel beneath a mountain in [[Poland]].<ref name=Kaplan/> Duncan Roads, editor of [[Nexus (magazine)|''Nexus'' magazine]], has pointed out that the \"Nazis on the Moon trope\" is linked to wild speculations about Nazi anti-gravitational technology, such as Witkowski's Die Glocke.<ref>{{cite news |last=Power |first=Ed |date=July 18, 2019 |title=Why are we still obsessed with the idea of Nazis on the Moon? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/still-obsessed-idea-nazis-moon/|work=Daily Telegraph |location=London }}</ref>\n\nJournalist Patrick J. Kiger wrote that German propaganda of fictional ''Wunderwaffen'' combined with the secrecy surrounding actual advanced technology such as the [[V-2]] rocket captured at war's end by the U.S. military helped spawn \"sensational book-length exposes, web sites, and legions of enthusiasts who revel in rumors of science fiction-like weapons supposedly invented by Hitler\u2019s scientists\". According to Kiger, Die Glocke is a popular example of such legends and speculation, citing former [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace scientist]] David Myhra's contention that if antigravity devices actually existed, the Germans, desperate to stop the Allies advance, would have used them.<ref name=secret>{{cite web|url=http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/hitler-s-stealth-fighter-3942/nazi-secret-weapons-1#ixzz0uXSU8IRo|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226104846/http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/episode/hitler-s-stealth-fighter-3942/nazi-secret-weapons-1|archive-date=26 February 2010|publisher=[[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]]|first=Patrick J.|last=Kiger|title=Nazi Secret Weapons|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\n*Die Glocke and other purported Nazi ''Wunderwaffen'' have been dramatized in the video game ''[[Call of Duty]]''.<ref name=\"Tack\">{{cite web |last1=Tack |first1=Daniel |title=Bringing The Horror Of Call of Duty: WWII Nazi Zombies To Life |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/08/09/bringing-the-horror-of-call-of-duty-nazi-zombies-to-life.aspx |website=Gameinformer.com |publisher=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> \n*Die Glocke figures in the backstory of the 2006 [[James Rollins]] action-adventure novel ''Black Order''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boucher |first=Rod |date=March 17, 2007 |title=Nazi master race revisited |work=The Mercury |location=Hobart, Australia |page=B9 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYJB\">{{cite web |last1=Fortier |first1=Ron |title=Black Order: A Sigma Force Novel |url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/black-order-sigma-force-novel |website=nyjournalofbooks.com |publisher=New York Journal of Books |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n*Die Glocke was the focus of a 2014 episode of ''[[In Search of Aliens]]''.<ref name=\"Colavito\" /><ref name=\"HC\">{{cite web |title=In Search of Aliens |url=https://www.history.com/shows/in-search-of-aliens/season-1/episode-2 |date=1 August 2014 |website=[[The History Channel]] |publisher=[[A&E Networks]] |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref>  \n*Die Glocke figures in the backstory of the 2013 [[A. G. Riddle]] action-adventure novel ''The Atlantis Gene''. <ref name=\"Riddle2013\">{{cite book|author=A. G. Riddle|authorlink=A. G. Riddle|title=The Atlantis Gene|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2YSmwEACAAJ|accessdate=25 January 2020|series=Origin mystery|volume=1|year=2013|publisher=A. G. Riddle|isbn=978-1-940026-01-5}}</ref>\n*The structures at Wenceslas Mine are featured in Series 3 episode 6 of Abandoned Engineering on the UK TV channel [[Yesterday (TV channel)|Yesterday]]. ''Igor Witkowski'' appears on the program and explains his theory about ''Die Glocke''\n*Die Glocke is featured as a plot device in Season 4 of the [[12 Monkeys (TV series)]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Nazism and occultism]]\n* [[Nazi UFOs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist |refs=\n<ref name=Kingsepp>{{cite journal |doi=10.1163/15700593-01902009 |title=Scholarship as Simulacrum: The Case of Hitler's Monsters |journal=Aries |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=265\u2013281 |year=2019 |last1=Kingsepp |first1=Eva |quote=One of these \u2018methodologically sound\u2019 books is Nick Cook\u2019s (in)famous ''The Hunt for Zero Point: Inside the Classified World of Antigravity Technology'' (2002), where a new amazing secret Nazi super weapon, the \u201cNazi Bell\u201d/\u201cdie Glocke\u201d, was introduced to the English-speaking audience. There is no critical reflection whatsoever regarding the poor credibility regarding \u201cdie Glocke\u201d, which is not surprising, as the general impression of ''Hitler\u2019s Monsters'' is that it aims at providing support for spectacular ideas rather than critically examining them. }}</ref>\n<ref name=Strube>{{cite journal |issn=2053-7158 |last=Strube |first=Julian |editor-last1=Elwing |editor-first1=Jimmy |editor-last2=Roukema |editor-first2=Aren |title=Hitler's Monsters: A Supernatural History of the Third Reich |url=http://correspondencesjournal.com/ojs/ojs/index.php/home/article/viewFile/56/56 |journal=Correspondences: Online Journal for the Academic Study of Western Esotericism |quote=These problems resurface in the chapters of Part Three, for instance when Kurlander cites from the reservoir of post-war conspiracy theories: his jaw dropping  discussion of a topic like the alleged super weapon, die Glocke, only serves, again, to suggest that the large amount of such tales hints at some obscure kernel of truth. }}</ref>\n<ref name=Kaplan>{{cite news |last=Kaplan |first=Sarah |date=August 28, 2015 |title=A frenzy in Poland over the latest mysterious 'Nazi gold train' |work=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/08/28/a-frenzy-in-poland-over-the-latest-mysterious-nazi-gold-train/|quote=On the corners of the Internet inclined toward conspiracy, theories circulate that \"Die Glocke\" \u2013 a purported Nazi superweapon that has so far only been found in the pages of science fiction novels \u2013 might be hidden somewhere beneath those ancient mountains.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category|Die Glocke}}\n* {{cite book | last = Cook | first = Nick | authorlink = Nick Cook (writer) | title = The Hunt for Zero Point: Inside the Classified World of Antigravity Technology | publisher = Century| year = 20